But let's say you want to use a library that doesn't

229
00:13:43,139 --> 00:13:44,619
have config for native image.

230
00:13:44,619 --> 00:13:46,779
Maybe they haven't added the config yet,

231
00:13:46,779 --> 00:13:49,820
or maybe your company has some internal library SDK

232
00:13:49,820 --> 00:13:52,059
that is not compatible with native image.

233
00:13:52,059 --> 00:13:53,940
So what to do in that case?

234
00:13:53,940 --> 00:13:56,619
Now, there could be a few solutions to that.

235
00:13:56,619 --> 00:13:59,419
One is if, like in my other demo,

236
00:13:59,419 --> 00:14:01,259
if you are on a version of a framework that

237
00:14:01,259 --> 00:14:03,180
is compatible with native image and offers

238
00:14:03,180 --> 00:14:05,900
some features for native image, such as, for example,

239
00:14:05,900 --> 00:14:09,619
here I am on Spring Boot 3.4.

240
00:14:09,619 --> 00:14:13,979
But anything above Spring Boot 3.0 and higher would work.

241
00:14:13,979 --> 00:14:17,539
So what you can do is you can generate hints programmatically.

242
00:14:17,539 --> 00:14:19,620
So you can instruct Spring to generate

243
00:14:19,620 --> 00:14:22,099
hints for those places in your application

244
00:14:22,099 --> 00:14:23,699
where reflection will occur.

245
00:14:23,699 --> 00:14:26,379
And Spring will solve this for you.

246
00:14:26,379 --> 00:14:28,500
So let's see this in action.

247
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:31,300
And for that, I have this app.

248
00:14:31,300 --> 00:14:35,139
And here I have my little reflection controller.

249
00:14:35,139 --> 00:14:37,139
So one thing that I want to mention here

250
00:14:37,139 --> 00:14:41,020
is you can say that I'm trying to make a reflective call

251
00:14:41,020 --> 00:14:44,939
to this message field in the message class over here.

252
00:14:44,939 --> 00:14:47,060
But I'm doing so, as you can tell,

253
00:14:47,060 --> 00:14:50,419
in a less maybe predictable way, or maybe not in the way

254
00:14:50,419 --> 00:14:51,460
you would write it.

255
00:14:51,460 --> 00:14:54,020
And that is to try and outsmart native image.

256
00:14:54,020 --> 00:14:56,900
Because a more predictable, more reasonable, more sane

257
00:14:56,900 --> 00:15:00,220
reflection call, native image can figure out out of the box.

258
00:15:00,220 --> 00:15:03,099
It does have limited but support for reflection out of the box.

259
00:15:03,099 --> 00:15:05,699
That's why we are trying to go ahead and outsmart native image

260
00:15:05,699 --> 00:15:06,699
here.

261
00:15:06,699 --> 00:15:09,699
So to make this work and to make this visible for native image,

262
00:15:09,699 --> 00:15:13,699
what I can do, because I have support from Spring for me,

263
00:15:13,699 --> 00:15:16,379
I can do register reflection for binding.

264
00:15:16,379 --> 00:15:18,259
And I have my import added.

265
00:15:18,259 --> 00:15:20,979
So now I can say, hey, my reflection

266
00:15:20,979 --> 00:15:23,740
will occur here in the message class.

267
00:15:23,740 --> 00:15:26,340
Please generate hints for me.

268
00:15:26,340 --> 00:15:28,780
And I didn't build it before to try and save us

269
00:15:28,780 --> 00:15:30,500
40 seconds of time.

270
00:15:30,500 --> 00:15:32,500
But let's go ahead and build this now

271
00:15:32,500 --> 00:15:35,020
and see if this will work.

272
00:15:35,020 --> 00:15:36,939
So this is Spring Boot.

273
00:15:36,939 --> 00:15:40,340
And we are again doing native, native, compile.

274
00:15:41,340 --> 00:15:41,819
OK.

275
00:15:41,819 --> 00:15:43,020
So our build has started.

276
00:15:43,020 --> 00:15:45,340
As it started, I want to show you two more things related

277
00:15:45,340 --> 00:15:48,220
to reflection and how you can programmatically generate

278
00:15:48,220 --> 00:15:50,139
config files for native image.

279
00:15:50,139 --> 00:15:51,460
So this is one way to do it.

280
00:15:51,460 --> 00:15:54,139
And this is the one that existed for a while in Spring.

281
00:15:54,139 --> 00:15:55,620
Now, in the upcoming release, they

282
00:15:55,620 --> 00:15:57,259
are also introducing a new way.

283
00:15:57,259 --> 00:16:01,020
So here I'm handling reflection and writing the annotation

284
00:16:01,020 --> 00:16:04,979
on the caller side, so where my reflection call originates.

285
00:16:04,979 --> 00:16:06,979
But they are also experimenting with a new way

286
00:16:06,979 --> 00:16:08,900
where you can add a reflection to the call.

287
00:16:08,900 --> 00:16:10,460
They are experimenting with a new way

288
00:16:10,460 --> 00:16:12,979
where you can annotate my callee side,

289
00:16:12,979 --> 00:16:15,379
so where the reflection call needs to end up.

290
00:16:15,379 --> 00:16:18,460
And I can say here reflective and add reflective scan

291
00:16:18,460 --> 00:16:19,740
on my main method.

292
00:16:19,740 --> 00:16:22,180
And this will make this class or field visible

293
00:16:22,180 --> 00:16:25,539
in terms of reflection to all the possible places in my app

294
00:16:25,539 --> 00:16:28,259
that might call this method or this field.

295
00:16:28,259 --> 00:16:29,580
So you can decide for yourself.

296
00:16:29,580 --> 00:16:32,259
Either you want to do it where your call originates

297
00:16:32,259 --> 00:16:34,939
or where it's supposed to end up.

298
00:16:34,939 --> 00:16:37,060
Now, this is not even the complete story yet.

299
00:16:37,180 --> 00:16:39,379
Spring offers you yet another way

300
00:16:39,379 --> 00:16:42,979
to make reflection or resources or serialization work.

301
00:16:42,979 --> 00:16:46,379
And they have this nice runtime hints registrar API

302
00:16:46,379 --> 00:16:48,300
where I can say, hey, I want to access

303
00:16:48,300 --> 00:16:50,020
this resource at runtime.

304
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:52,259
Please make it available to native image.

305
00:16:52,259 --> 00:16:54,659
Please generate hints for resources.

306
00:16:54,659 --> 00:16:57,780
And this is a nice flexible API because along with resources,

307
00:16:57,780 --> 00:17:03,659
I can do something like hints.reflection or, yeah,

308
00:17:03,659 --> 00:17:05,020
reflection or GNI.

309
00:17:05,020 --> 00:17:08,259
And it will also generate hints for those things.

310
00:17:08,259 --> 00:17:11,340
So those are three possible ways to do so from Spring,

311
00:17:11,340 --> 00:17:13,379
but also similar exists in other frameworks

312
00:17:13,379 --> 00:17:16,740
when they can help generate files for native image.

313
00:17:16,740 --> 00:17:20,220
Now that our build is complete, let's go ahead and run it.

314
00:17:20,220 --> 00:17:22,620
So target demo.

315
00:17:22,620 --> 00:17:25,460
And our endpoint that is responsible for reflection

316
00:17:25,460 --> 00:17:26,419
is this one.

317
00:17:26,419 --> 00:17:28,859
So we retrieved our message.

318
00:17:28,859 --> 00:17:31,699
And in a similar fashion, we can do resource.

319
00:17:31,699 --> 00:17:35,939
And we see that we can also load the resource.

320
00:17:35,939 --> 00:17:39,099
So this was about making reflection

321
00:17:39,099 --> 00:17:42,460
and other dynamic Java features work for your application

322
00:17:42,460 --> 00:17:44,180
from a framework.

323
00:17:44,180 --> 00:17:46,580
To finish this part, so you can generate hints

324
00:17:46,580 --> 00:17:48,979
from your framework if you have framework support.

325
00:17:48,979 --> 00:17:50,900
Now, let's say you want to use a library,

326
00:17:50,900 --> 00:17:52,740
but you are on a version of a framework that

327
00:17:52,740 --> 00:17:54,139
doesn't work with GraalVM.

328
00:17:54,139 --> 00:17:55,500
The library doesn't have config.

329
00:17:55,500 --> 00:17:58,539
Seems like you are out of luck and out of options.

330
00:17:58,539 --> 00:17:59,580
Well, not just yet.

331
00:17:59,580 --> 00:18:02,740
So if you don't have any support from your library on framework,

332
00:18:02,740 --> 00:18:04,460
there is one more thing that you can do.

333
00:18:04,460 --> 00:18:07,500
And that is you can use this tracing agent from native image.

334
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:10,060
So this is an agent that comes with native image, where

335
00:18:10,060 --> 00:18:11,819
you can run your application on the JVM

336
00:18:11,819 --> 00:18:14,220
with the agent attached to the process.

337
00:18:14,220 --> 00:18:17,419
And you can show us, show the application what

338
00:18:17,419 --> 00:18:20,340
it's supposed to be doing, apply relevant workload.

339
00:18:20,340 --> 00:18:22,819
And then the agent will observe your application behavior,

340
00:18:22,819 --> 00:18:25,379
in particular, all those things around reflection.

341
00:18:25,379 --> 00:18:27,340
And it will output configuration files

342
00:18:27,340 --> 00:18:29,740
that can native image pick up and automatically

343
00:18:29,740 --> 00:18:31,740
resolve those calls for you.

344
00:18:31,740 --> 00:18:34,059
So the agent will generate those files for you

345
00:18:34,059 --> 00:18:36,179
in a semi-automatic way.

346
00:18:36,179 --> 00:18:38,340
It will not always be complete, maybe.

347
00:18:38,340 --> 00:18:40,580
Or maybe you need to apply really good workloads.

348
00:18:40,580 --> 00:18:43,780
But this is a good way to do this JSON

349
00:18:43,780 --> 00:18:46,259
writing in a semi-automatic way, rather than

350
00:18:46,259 --> 00:18:48,379
writing the files yourself.

351
00:18:48,379 --> 00:18:51,739
And then the last is, if you have this one small call that

352
00:18:51,739 --> 00:18:53,259
just doesn't work with native image,

353
00:18:53,259 --> 00:18:54,980
but you know exactly where it appears,

354
00:18:54,980 --> 00:18:56,780
you can do so yourself manually.

355
00:18:56,780 --> 00:18:59,540
You can just write this configuration file yourself

356
00:18:59,540 --> 00:19:01,660
from a JSON format.

357
00:19:01,660 --> 00:19:04,580
So this was maybe a bit too complicated and a lot of text.

358
00:19:04,580 --> 00:19:06,619
But really, if you want to make libraries work

359
00:19:06,619 --> 00:19:08,499
with scroll via native image, this

360
00:19:08,499 --> 00:19:10,360
is the things you need to do.

361
00:19:10,360 --> 00:19:12,900
And I hope, especially if you're starting a new application,

362
00:19:12,900 --> 00:19:15,499
that you never need to go beyond those three points,

363
00:19:15,499 --> 00:19:17,699
that either a library will ship a config,

364
00:19:17,699 --> 00:19:20,540
or it will be available in our centralized repository,

365
00:19:20,540 --> 00:19:23,860
especially for new applications.

366
00:19:23,860 --> 00:19:26,220
So we were talking about writing applications

367
00:19:26,220 --> 00:19:28,020
and using the libraries.

368
00:19:28,020 --> 00:19:29,660
Now, let's talk about another thing.

369
00:19:29,660 --> 00:19:32,220
And that is how you can optimize your native executables

370
00:19:32,220 --> 00:19:34,220
with native image.

371
00:19:34,220 --> 00:19:37,499
So there are many, many optimization levels

372
00:19:37,499 --> 00:19:39,259
in native image that you can choose from.

373
00:19:39,259 --> 00:19:41,220
And I feel like this is less known.

374
00:19:41,220 --> 00:19:43,020
So maybe, if you want, you can take a photo

375
00:19:43,020 --> 00:19:44,420
and you can look into this after.

376
00:19:44,420 --> 00:19:46,299
But basically, you can set those flags

377
00:19:46,299 --> 00:19:48,980
to set your preferable optimization

378
00:19:48,980 --> 00:19:50,619
level in native image.

379
00:19:50,619 --> 00:19:55,100
So the dash o zero is usually used for debugging purposes.

380
00:19:55,179 --> 00:19:57,220
This is no optimizations at all.

381
00:19:57,220 --> 00:20:01,340
Then one through three, this is optimization level.

382
00:20:01,340 --> 00:20:03,220
as going from basic optimizations

383
00:20:03,220 --> 00:20:06,220
through advanced to full optimizations.

384
00:20:06,220 --> 00:20:07,980
Here I need to mention that Dash O3 is

385
00:20:07,980 --> 00:20:10,260
available in Oracle Growl VM.

386
00:20:10,260 --> 00:20:12,640
Now, Dash OB optimizes for build time.

387
00:20:12,640 --> 00:20:15,860
This is what I was using in our dictionary application.

388
00:20:15,860 --> 00:20:19,139
And then Dash OS optimizes for size.

389
00:20:19,139 --> 00:20:21,420
Now, for me, this is not the most common concern,

390
00:20:21,420 --> 00:20:23,540
like the size of my native executable.

391
00:20:23,540 --> 00:20:25,860
But people in our community told us many times

392
00:20:25,860 --> 00:20:27,660
they don't want to have something like this.

393
00:20:27,660 --> 00:20:30,260
And in my measurements, again, I tried it

394
00:20:30,260 --> 00:20:31,500
on a Spring Boot application.

395
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:35,139
It shaves off around 1 third of your application size.

396
00:20:35,139 --> 00:20:37,700
So if you want to maybe have smaller binaries,

397
00:20:37,700 --> 00:20:40,099
Dash OS would be the way to go.

398
00:20:40,099 --> 00:20:42,779
Now, if you want to optimize for the best peak throughput,

399
00:20:42,779 --> 00:20:45,740
and I hear this comment a lot about IoT and JIT

400
00:20:45,740 --> 00:20:48,540
and how native image would now be as fast as JIT,

401
00:20:48,540 --> 00:20:51,459
because JIT optimizes your application on the go.

402
00:20:51,459 --> 00:20:53,979
Now, in general, it's an interesting theoretical

403
00:20:53,979 --> 00:20:57,420
discussion whether or not IoT code can be as fast as JIT.

404
00:20:57,420 --> 00:20:59,959
If you are curious, we can chat about it during the break.

405
00:20:59,959 --> 00:21:02,000
I will be very happy to do so.

406
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:03,799
But here are optimization strategies

407
00:21:03,799 --> 00:21:06,359
that you can use for the best peak throughput.

408
00:21:06,359 --> 00:21:09,479
So one thing that you need, you definitely need PGO.

409
00:21:09,479 --> 00:21:11,560
This is the flag that triggers our profile-guided

410
00:21:11,560 --> 00:21:12,799
optimizations.

411
00:21:12,799 --> 00:21:14,299
And the way this works is that you

412
00:21:14,299 --> 00:21:16,640
can build an instrumented version of your native

413
00:21:16,640 --> 00:21:19,679
executable, apply relevant workloads,

414
00:21:19,679 --> 00:21:21,560
observe your application behavior,

415
00:21:21,560 --> 00:21:23,600
and then after you shut down the application,

416
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:27,000
it will produce profiles file that you can then feed,

417
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,119
or rather automatically pick up when

418
00:21:29,160 --> 00:21:31,359
you build your native image for production.

419
00:21:31,359 --> 00:21:34,479
And this way, we have access to what your application will

420
00:21:34,479 --> 00:21:36,640
do at runtime, and specifically, which

421
00:21:36,640 --> 00:21:39,560
parts of your application would be more hot.

422
00:21:39,560 --> 00:21:41,359
Now, here people often tell me, but you

423
00:21:41,359 --> 00:21:43,160
know the JVM profile is on the go.

424
00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:46,280
It always adapts to what your application is doing.

425
00:21:46,280 --> 00:21:48,679
That is true, but what is also true

426
00:21:48,679 --> 00:21:52,880
is that a lot of profiling the JVM does during startup,

427
00:21:52,880 --> 00:21:55,759
and then it still observes and profiles your application,

428
00:21:55,759 --> 00:21:58,079
but many of those key assumptions

429
00:21:58,079 --> 00:21:59,840
are made during the startup.

430
00:21:59,840 --> 00:22:01,560
While native image, even though it

431
00:22:01,560 --> 00:22:04,280
doesn't have access to the runtime information of your app,

432
00:22:04,280 --> 00:22:07,960
it indeed instead has access to this closed world

433
00:22:07,960 --> 00:22:09,599
of your application, where everything

434
00:22:09,599 --> 00:22:12,080
there is to know about your app is already known.

435
00:22:12,080 --> 00:22:14,720
So I would say that native image does a different kind

436
00:22:14,720 --> 00:22:18,759
of profiling, but it also can give you good peak throughput.

437
00:22:18,759 --> 00:22:20,679
In terms of other performance optimizations,

438
00:22:20,679 --> 00:22:22,140
one more thing that I can recommend

439
00:22:22,140 --> 00:22:24,440
is using JVM GC for peak throughput,

440
00:22:24,440 --> 00:22:26,280
especially if you have an application that

441
00:22:26,280 --> 00:22:28,979
is long running, does a lot of allocation,

442
00:22:28,979 --> 00:22:31,560
uses a lot of threads, then JVM probably

443
00:22:31,560 --> 00:22:33,759
will be your best shot.

444
00:22:33,759 --> 00:22:36,720
One new GC thing that we introduced in the last release

445
00:22:36,720 --> 00:22:38,800
is now we have this new compacting policy

446
00:22:38,800 --> 00:22:41,920
for the serial GC, which is less tailored towards peak

447
00:22:41,920 --> 00:22:44,640
throughput, but it's rather targeting making sure

448
00:22:44,640 --> 00:22:48,640
that you will never go overboard with peak memory usage.

449
00:22:48,640 --> 00:22:50,800
So if you want to have good peak throughput,

450
00:22:50,800 --> 00:22:52,759
but you want to make sure that you will never

451
00:22:52,759 --> 00:22:56,200
go overboard with memory usage, use this compacting GC policy.

452
00:22:57,200 --> 00:22:59,519
And then the last flag here is a mark native.

453
00:22:59,519 --> 00:23:02,200
So this says, hey, I'm using this machine,

454
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:04,440
and I will be building and deploying on this machine.

455
00:23:04,440 --> 00:23:07,280
Please specialize for the specific architecture

456
00:23:07,280 --> 00:23:09,519
and hardware features of this machine,

457
00:23:09,519 --> 00:23:11,679
as opposed to building a binary that

458
00:23:11,679 --> 00:23:15,599
will be very compatible with many possible versions

459
00:23:15,599 --> 00:23:16,879
of the same architecture.

460
00:23:16,879 --> 00:23:18,459
So this will specialize for the machine

461
00:23:18,459 --> 00:23:20,000
that you are building on.

462
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:21,920
Now, I was debating whether we have enough time

463
00:23:21,920 --> 00:23:24,119
for benchmarking, and we don't have enough time

464
00:23:24,119 --> 00:23:25,239
for proper benchmarking.

465
00:23:25,280 --> 00:23:27,319
But I know that otherwise you wouldn't believe me

466
00:23:27,319 --> 00:23:28,560
about all those flags.

467
00:23:28,560 --> 00:23:32,599
So let's see if we can do at least a quick round

468
00:23:32,599 --> 00:23:34,000
of benchmarking.

469
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:37,440
For this, we will run our same dictionary application,

470
00:23:37,440 --> 00:23:41,039
only we need to go back to the dictionary folder.

471
00:23:41,039 --> 00:23:43,800
So what I will do here, I will run my application three times.

472
00:23:43,800 --> 00:23:46,479
First, I will run it on C2.

473
00:23:46,479 --> 00:23:49,560
So this is in the JVM mode with the C2 compiler,

474
00:23:49,560 --> 00:23:52,280
same compiler as in your, let's say, OpenJDK.

475
00:23:52,280 --> 00:23:54,119
And the script will start my application,

476
00:23:54,119 --> 00:23:55,399
the same dictionary app.

477
00:23:55,399 --> 00:23:58,560
And then we will use the benchmarking tool called Hey

478
00:23:58,560 --> 00:24:01,560
to send 500,000 requests to our app.

479
00:24:01,560 --> 00:24:03,720
In the beginning, we will also wait five seconds

480
00:24:03,720 --> 00:24:06,879
to give the JVM a bit of time to start.

481
00:24:06,879 --> 00:24:08,160
So we run our application.

482
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:12,840
Our peak throughput is around 50k requests per second.

483
00:24:12,840 --> 00:24:14,519
Let's get a native version.

484
00:24:14,519 --> 00:24:19,119
Only let's do the comparison side by side.

485
00:24:19,119 --> 00:24:21,160
So now I will send the exact same load.

486
00:24:21,160 --> 00:24:23,799
And I will also wait like I had to wait with the JVM.

487
00:24:23,980 --> 00:24:27,199
But we will, again, save 500,000 to our application,

488
00:24:27,199 --> 00:24:29,160
now just the native version.

489
00:24:29,160 --> 00:24:32,519
So here we were at 50k requests per second.

490
00:24:32,519 --> 00:24:36,040
Who thinks that the native version will be faster?

491
00:24:36,040 --> 00:24:37,639
Well, you know that I work on GraalVM,

492
00:24:37,639 --> 00:24:39,519
so I could have applied some of your tricks

493
00:24:39,519 --> 00:24:42,000
to kind of seem faster, right?

494
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:43,760
But let's see.

495
00:24:43,760 --> 00:24:48,079
So this one is at 42, a bit slower than the JVM.

496
00:24:48,079 --> 00:24:50,600
But this was our native image out of the box.

497
00:24:50,600 --> 00:24:51,980
So this is the experience you will

498
00:24:51,980 --> 00:24:55,299
get if you're not applying any optimization yourself.

499
00:24:55,299 --> 00:24:59,340
Now, what happens if I go ahead and I apply those three flags

500
00:24:59,340 --> 00:25:00,660
that I mentioned?

501
00:25:00,660 --> 00:25:03,459
So bench native optimized.

502
00:25:03,459 --> 00:25:07,859
And this is a version with PGO, with JVM GC, and M-Arc native.

503
00:25:07,859 --> 00:25:10,699
And let me just push those side by side

504
00:25:10,699 --> 00:25:14,419
so we can compare when we get the final numbers.

505
00:25:14,419 --> 00:25:16,739
OK, so 50k, 42k.

506
00:25:16,739 --> 00:25:18,639
And once again, disclaimer, by no means

507
00:25:18,639 --> 00:25:20,179
this is scientific benchmarking.

508
00:25:20,179 --> 00:25:22,500
Scientific benchmarking will require at least like half

509
00:25:22,500 --> 00:25:25,380
an hour and a proper isolated machine.

510
00:25:25,380 --> 00:25:28,220
But close enough for a conference session.

511
00:25:28,220 --> 00:25:30,419
So 50k, 42k.

512
00:25:30,419 --> 00:25:34,060
And here with the optimization, we are at 58k.

513
00:25:34,060 --> 00:25:37,419
So I'm not necessarily claiming that a native app will always

514
00:25:37,419 --> 00:25:38,739
be faster than the JVM.

515
00:25:38,739 --> 00:25:40,540
But what I rather want to show here

516
00:25:40,540 --> 00:25:42,980
is that the impact of those three optimizations,

517
00:25:42,980 --> 00:25:45,739
if you take the time and effort to apply them,

518
00:25:45,739 --> 00:25:46,980
can be substantial.

519
00:25:46,980 --> 00:25:48,419
So if you want to have good peaks

520
00:25:48,419 --> 00:25:51,579
throughput on native image, test.

521
00:25:51,579 --> 00:25:53,980
And we can play with the combination of the flags.

522
00:25:53,980 --> 00:25:59,340
But most likely, PGO, JVM, and M-Arc native is what you want.

523
00:25:59,340 --> 00:26:01,299
Now, talking about the features that you

524
00:26:01,299 --> 00:26:05,060
might want to use in production working with native image,

525
00:26:05,060 --> 00:26:09,019
let me go back to my agenda.

526
00:26:09,019 --> 00:26:10,419
Here it is.

527
00:26:10,419 --> 00:26:12,260
So I want to very briefly say a few things

528
00:26:12,260 --> 00:26:13,899
about development strategies, and then

529
00:26:13,899 --> 00:26:15,500
building and deploying.

530
00:26:15,500 --> 00:26:18,100
So for development, what I want to recommend to you

531
00:26:18,100 --> 00:26:20,019
is you keep developing on the JVM.

532
00:26:20,019 --> 00:26:22,940
And then you compile to native once in a while,

533
00:26:22,940 --> 00:26:26,299
maybe in your CICD, or once a day,

534
00:26:26,299 --> 00:26:28,220
or if you are touching things that you know

535
00:26:28,220 --> 00:26:29,820
are sensitive to native image.

536
00:26:29,820 --> 00:26:31,980
So if you're introducing a new dependency,

537
00:26:31,980 --> 00:26:33,340
if you are touching your reflection

538
00:26:33,340 --> 00:26:35,299
and serialization resources, but you

539
00:26:35,299 --> 00:26:37,859
don't need to recompile every five minutes,

540
00:26:37,859 --> 00:26:41,019
or if I'm introducing minor changes to my business logic,

541
00:26:41,019 --> 00:26:42,220
this is just not necessary.

542
00:26:42,220 --> 00:26:44,380
It will be a waste of your time.

543
00:26:44,380 --> 00:26:46,260
So a good practice is develop on the JVM

544
00:26:46,260 --> 00:26:48,540
and then compile to native, as I mentioned, in CICD,

545
00:26:48,540 --> 00:26:50,899
maybe once a day, or before the deployment,

546
00:26:50,899 --> 00:26:52,780
when you're ready to deploy, or if you

547
00:26:52,780 --> 00:26:54,260
touch something major in your app,

548
00:26:54,260 --> 00:26:56,859
such as introduced a new dependency.

549
00:26:56,859 --> 00:26:59,060
Now, for building and deploying, native image

550
00:26:59,060 --> 00:27:01,179
produces native executables that are

551
00:27:01,179 --> 00:27:04,340
specific to a platform and operating system,

552
00:27:04,340 --> 00:27:06,220
because we need some JDK classes that

553
00:27:06,220 --> 00:27:08,260
are specific for each platform.

554
00:27:08,260 --> 00:27:10,060
Now, there are multiple ways around it.

555
00:27:10,060 --> 00:27:11,619
You can do container images.

556
00:27:11,619 --> 00:27:13,940
You can use something like Buildpacks for that,

557
00:27:14,500 --> 00:27:16,060
or another thing you can do is you

558
00:27:16,060 --> 00:27:18,419
can use CICD systems, such as, for example,

559
00:27:18,419 --> 00:27:21,380
I'm using for my demo projects, GitHub Actions.

560
00:27:21,380 --> 00:27:23,780
And there, you can just set up builds for each platform.

561
00:27:23,780 --> 00:27:26,619
And you can just build there and deliver to whatever platforms

562
00:27:26,619 --> 00:27:28,540
you need to deliver.

563
00:27:28,540 --> 00:27:30,660
So this will be my tips for that.

564
00:27:30,660 --> 00:27:33,299
Now, I want to show you one last thing for security

565
00:27:33,299 --> 00:27:34,459
and monitoring.

